{"title_page": "Class-T amplifier", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=September 2011}}\n[[File:Tripath amplifier modules.jpg|thumb|Two Tripath chipset Class T stereo amplifier modules. TA2024 6+6W to the left, TA2020 20+20W to the right]]\n\n'''Class T''' was a registered trademark for a [[class-D amplifier|switching (class-D) audio amplifier]], used for [[Tripath]]'s amplifier technologies (patent filed on Jun 20, 1996). Similar designs have now been widely adopted by different manufacturers.<ref name=\"shook\">{{cite web | url=https://spectrum.ieee.org/tech-history/silicon-revolution/25-microchips-that-shook-the-world/ | title=25 Microchips That Shook the World | date=1 May 2009 | author=Brian Santo | publisher=[[Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers|IEEE]] | accessdate=2014-07-04}}</ref>\n\n==Amplifier==\nThe covered products use a class-D amplifier combined with proprietary techniques to control the [[pulse width modulation]] to produce what is claimed to be better performance than other class-D amplifier designs. Among the publicly disclosed differences is real time control of the switching frequency depending on the input signal and amplified output. One of the amplifiers, the TA2020, was named one of the twenty-five chips that 'shook the world\" by the ''[[IEEE Spectrum]]'' magazine.<ref name=\"shook\"/>\n\nThe control signals in Class T amplifiers may be computed using [[digital signal processing]] or fully analog techniques.  Currently available implementations use a loop similar to a higher order [[Delta-sigma modulation|Delta-Sigma]] (\u0394\u03a3) (or sigma-delta) modulator, with an internal digital clock to control the sample comparator. The two key aspects of this topology are that (1), feedback is taken directly from the switching node rather than the filtered output, and (2), the higher order loop provides much higher loop gain at high audio frequencies than would be possible in a conventional single pole amplifier.\n\n[[File:Blaupunkt PA2150 T-Amp top.jpeg|thumb|Blaupunkt PA2150 T-Amp, \"Powered by Tripath\"]]\nFinancial difficulties caused Tripath to file for [[Chapter 11]] bankruptcy protection on 8 February 2007. Tripath's stock and intellectual property were purchased later that year by [[Cirrus Logic]].\n\n==Products and applications==\n\nTripath used to sell the amplifiers as [[Integrated circuit|chip]]s, or as [[chipset]]s, to be integrated into products by other companies in several countries. For example:\n* [[Sony]], [[Panasonic]] and [[Blaupunkt]] use them in several [[car stereo]]s and integrated [[home cinema]] systems\n* [[Apple Computer]] used them in their [[Power Mac G4 Cube]], [[Power Mac G4]] (Digital audio), [[eMac]] and [[iMac|iMac (Flat Panel)]] computers\n* [[Audio Research]], an audio electronics company, formerly an exclusive tube circuit specialist, produced a Tripath-based audiophile amplifier.\n* [[Sonneteer (company)|Sonneteer]], a British hifi company, analogue amplifier and technology specialists, manufactured the Bronte amplifier (1999),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sonneteer.com/history/digital-party-like-its-1999/|title=Digital Party like it\u2019s 1999|date=July 6, 2011}}</ref> based around a Tripath class-T module.\n* [[Bel Canto Design]] used them in their eVo range of amplifiers.\n* [[Virtue Audio]] used them in their ONE, TWO, and Sensation range of amplifiers from around 2008\u20132014.\n* [[Sonneteer (company)|Sonneteer]], a British hifi company, analogue amplifier and technology specialists, manufactured under Sub Brand Bard Audio, the BardThree amplifier (2005),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.6moons.com/audioreviews/sonneteer/bard.html|title=6moons audio reviews: The Bard Audio wireless system by Sonneteer Audio|website=www.6moons.com}}</ref> based around a Tripath class-T chip and is/was known as the Plug Top or Rug Rat amp.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.google.com/patents?vid=USPAT5777512  US Patent for Class T amplifier]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Class T Amplifier}}\n[[Category:Audio amplifiers|T]]\n[[Category:Switching amplifiers]]\n[[Category:Electronic amplifiers]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=September 2011}}\n[[File:Tripath amplifier modules.jpg|thumb|Two Tripath chipset Class T stereo amplifier modules. TA2024 6+6W to the left, TA2020 20+20W to the right]]\n\n'''Class T''' was a registered trademark for a [[class-D amplifier|switching (class-D) audio amplifier]], used for [[Tripath]]'s amplifier technologies (patent filed on Jun 20, 1996). Similar designs have now been widely adopted by different manufacturers.<ref name=\"shook\">{{cite web | url=https://spectrum.ieee.org/tech-history/silicon-revolution/25-microchips-that-shook-the-world/ | title=25 Microchips That Shook the World | date=1 May 2009 | author=Brian Santo | publisher=[[Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers|IEEE]] | accessdate=2014-07-04}}</ref>\n\n==Amplifier==\nThe covered products use a class-D amplifier combined with proprietary techniques to control the [[pulse width modulation]] to produce what is claimed to be better performance than other class-D amplifier designs. Among the publicly disclosed differences is real time control of the switching frequency depending on the input signal and amplified output. One of the amplifiers, the TA2020, was named one of the twenty-five chips that 'shook the world\" by the ''[[IEEE Spectrum]]'' magazine.<ref name=\"shook\"/>\n\nThe control signals in Class T amplifiers may be computed using [[digital signal processing]] or fully analog techniques.  Currently available implementations use a loop similar to a higher order [[Delta-sigma modulation|Delta-Sigma]] (\u0394\u03a3) (or sigma-delta) modulator, with an internal digital clock to control the sample comparator. The two key aspects of this topology are that (1), feedback is taken directly from the switching node rather than the filtered output, and (2), the higher order loop provides much higher loop gain at high audio frequencies than would be possible in a conventional single pole amplifier.\n\n[[File:Blaupunkt PA2150 T-Amp top.jpeg|thumb|Blaupunkt PA2150 T-Amp, \"Powered by Tripath\"]]\nFinancial difficulties caused Tripath to file for [[Chapter 11]] bankruptcy protection on 8 February 2007. Tripath's stock and intellectual property were purchased later that year by [[Cirrus Logic]].\n\n==Products and applications==\n\nTripath used to sell the amplifiers as [[Integrated circuit|chip]]s, or as [[chipset]]s, to be integrated into products by other companies in several countries. For example:\n* [[Sony]], [[Panasonic]] and [[Blaupunkt]] use them in several [[car stereo]]s and integrated [[home cinema]] systems\n* [[Apple Computer]] used them in their [[Power Mac G4 Cube]], [[Power Mac G4]] (Digital audio), [[eMac]] and [[iMac|iMac (Flat Panel)]] computers\n* [[Audio Research]], an audio electronics company, formerly an exclusive tube circuit specialist, produced a Tripath-based audiophile amplifier.\n* [[Sonneteer (company)|Sonneteer]], a British hifi company, analogue amplifier and technology specialists, manufactured the Bronte amplifier (1999),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sonneteer.com/history/digital-party-like-its-1999/|title=Digital Party like it\u2019s 1999|date=July 6, 2011}}</ref> based around a Tripath class-T module.\n* [[Bel Canto Design]] used them in their eVo range of amplifiers.\n* [[Virtue Audio]] used them in their ONE, TWO, and Sensation range of amplifiers from around 2008\u20132014.\n* [[Sonneteer (company)|Sonneteer]], a British hifi company, analogue amplifier and technology specialists, manufactured under Sub Brand Bard Audio, the BardThree amplifier (2005),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.6moons.com/audioreviews/sonneteer/bard.html|title=6moons audio reviews: The Bard\u00a0Audio wireless system by Sonneteer Audio|website=www.6moons.com}}</ref> based around a Tripath class-T chip and is/was known as the Plug Top or Rug Rat amp.\n\n==References=